// EPSO AD5 Digital Skills — Question bank
// Mapped to DigComp 2.2 (JRC128415). 168 items across all 21 competences.
// Each: {i:id, c:competence "x.y", t:topic, d:difficulty 1-3, q:stem, o:[4 options], a:correct index, e:explanation}

window.QUESTIONS = [
    { i: "1.1.1", c: "1.1", t: "Search operators", d: 1, q: "You need to find PDF reports about EU asylum policy from official EU institutions only. Which approach is most efficient?", o: ["Type 'EU asylum reports' in a general search engine and skim the first 30 results", "Use the site:europa.eu and filetype:pdf operators alongside your keywords on a search engine", "Search inside Wikipedia first to identify primary sources, then follow the citation links", "Ask a generative AI chatbot for the latest reports and follow the citations it gives back"], a: 1, e: "Search operators (site:, filetype:, intitle:) narrow results to authoritative sources without skimming. Generative AI can hallucinate citations; Wikipedia is secondary; broad search wastes time." },
    { i: "1.1.2", c: "1.1", t: "Recommender systems", d: 2, q: "You notice your social-media feed shows almost only views you already agree with. The DigComp 2.2 framework calls this phenomenon a:", o: ["Phishing trap", "Filter bubble created by algorithmic personalisation", "Cookie wall", "Distributed denial-of-service effect"], a: 1, e: "A filter bubble arises when recommender algorithms personalise content based on prior engagement, narrowing exposure to alternative views." },
    { i: "1.1.3", c: "1.1", t: "Sponsored vs organic", d: 1, q: "In a search-engine results page, which signal most reliably distinguishes a paid advertisement from an organic result?", o: ["The result has a higher position on the page", "An explicit 'Sponsored' or 'Ad' label", "The URL contains 'https'", "The site has a professional design"], a: 1, e: "Search engines are legally required to label paid placements. Position, HTTPS and design quality are not reliable indicators of whether a result is paid." },
    { i: "1.1.4", c: "1.1", t: "AI text recognition", d: 2, q: "Which of the following is the LEAST reliable way to determine whether a text was generated by an AI system?", o: ["Cross-check specific verifiable factual claims that the text makes about people, dates, or events", "Look for vague generalities, unusually polished phrasing, and generic structure across paragraphs", "Run the text through an automated AI-detector tool that scores the probability of AI authorship", "Compare the writing style to the supposed author's known work, including word choice and rhythm"], a: 2, e: "Automated AI-detector tools have high false-positive and false-negative rates and are not considered reliable. Cross-checking facts, examining style, and detecting generic phrasing are more dependable signals." },
    { i: "1.1.5", c: "1.1", t: "Voice assistants", d: 1, q: "What is a key privacy consideration when using a voice assistant to search for information?", o: ["Voice queries stay on the device end-to-end and are typically processed locally without upload", "Voice queries may be transmitted to the provider's servers and retained as searchable data", "Voice queries route through the same channel as typed search and inherit the same data flow", "Voice queries bypass cookies, so the privacy concerns of typed web searches do not apply"], a: 1, e: "Voice queries are typically processed in the cloud and may be retained, reviewed, and used for service improvement depending on provider policies." },
    { i: "1.1.6", c: "1.1", t: "Search strategy", d: 1, q: "You are researching an unfamiliar legal topic. What is the most effective first step in building a search strategy?", o: ["Start with the most precise technical phrase you can think of and refine from the first results", "Identify a few authoritative domain sources for EU law (the EUR-Lex portal among them) and search inside", "Pick one search engine and stay with it across the project so the result set stays comparable", "Read every result on the first page in order to pick up context before narrowing the search"], a: 1, e: "Identifying authoritative domain-specific sources first (EUR-Lex, official journals, accredited databases) is more efficient than narrow keyword guessing or exhaustive reading." },
    { i: "1.1.7", c: "1.1", t: "RSS feeds", d: 2, q: "Which technology is best suited for monitoring updates from many official websites without manually visiting each one?", o: ["A virtual private network (VPN), routing traffic through a tunnel that surfaces page changes", "An RSS feed reader, with the user subscribed to each site's published feed in one consolidated app", "A persistent browser cookie, set by each site to flag the page when fresh content is published", "A bookmark folder, organised by topic, opened daily to skim the saved pages for new content"], a: 1, e: "RSS aggregates updates from many sources into a single feed. VPNs route traffic; cookies store state; bookmarks still require manual visits." },
    { i: "1.1.8", c: "1.1", t: "Direct ID search", d: 1, q: "On the EUR-Lex website, you know the exact CELEX number of a legal act. The most efficient retrieval method is:", o: ["Browse alphabetically through the directory of legal acts and look for the act by topic", "Enter the CELEX number in the 'Quick search' field at the top of the EUR-Lex page", "Type the title of the act into a general web search engine and follow the EUR-Lex link", "Email the EUR-Lex helpdesk with the CELEX number and ask them to send you the act"], a: 1, e: "When you have a unique identifier (CELEX, DOI, ISBN), direct ID search is the fastest path." },
    { i: "1.2.1", c: "1.2", t: "Malinformation", d: 2, q: "An employee leaks a genuine internal memo to an external journalist with the explicit aim of damaging a colleague's reputation. Under the UNESCO information-disorder taxonomy, this is best classified as:", o: ["Misinformation", "Disinformation", "Malinformation", "Whistleblowing"], a: 2, e: "Malinformation = information based on reality, used to inflict harm. Disinformation requires the information itself to be false; misinformation is false but unintentional. Whistleblowing concerns disclosure of wrongdoing in the public interest." },
    { i: "1.2.2", c: "1.2", t: "Misinformation vs disinformation", d: 2, q: "A friend forwards you a health claim that is factually wrong. The friend genuinely believes it is true. By UNESCO's definition this is:", o: ["Disinformation, because the claim shared with the recipient is factually false", "Misinformation, because the sender shares false content without any intent to harm", "Malinformation, because the claim is shared widely beyond the original sender's contacts", "Propaganda, because the shared claim influences the recipient's opinion on a health issue"], a: 1, e: "Misinformation = false content shared without intent to harm. Disinformation requires deliberate intent. The classification depends on intent, not on how widely it spreads." },
    { i: "1.2.3", c: "1.2", t: "AI hallucination", d: 2, q: "A generative-AI chatbot confidently cites a 2023 Court of Justice ruling that turns out not to exist. This output is best described as:", o: ["A bias in the training data", "A hallucination", "A prompt injection", "A privacy breach"], a: 1, e: "A hallucination is fluent, confident output that is unsupported by the model's input or by reality. Bias is systematic skew; prompt injection is adversarial input." },
    { i: "1.2.4", c: "1.2", t: "Source triangulation", d: 1, q: "You see a striking statistic on a blog. The most rigorous next step before citing it is:", o: ["Share the statistic forward because the source blog has a large and well-engaged readership", "Trace the statistic back to its primary source and check the methodology behind the figure", "Check whether other blogs repeat the same statistic and use the cross-citations as confirmation", "Trust the statistic if a generative AI tool, asked separately, also produces a similar figure"], a: 1, e: "Tracing a claim to its primary source is the gold standard. Repetition across secondary sources can amplify error; AI tools may regurgitate the same flawed source." },
    { i: "1.2.5", c: "1.2", t: "Deepfake indicators", d: 2, q: "Which of the following is the LEAST useful indicator that a video might be a deepfake?", o: ["Inconsistent lighting on the subject's face compared with the lighting visible on the background", "Unnatural blinking patterns or mouth synchronisation issues during the spoken passages of the clip", "The video is currently shared on social media platforms and circulated by users with reach", "Audio that does not match lip movement on close inspection of the speaker during the clip"], a: 2, e: "Sharing on social media is irrelevant to authenticity — both genuine and fake content circulate there. Lighting, blinking, and audio sync are recognised technical artefacts of synthetic media." },
    { i: "1.2.6", c: "1.2", t: "Primary vs secondary", d: 1, q: "For research on a recent EU regulation, which counts as the primary source?", o: ["A news analysis written by a domain reporter explaining the regulation soon after adoption", "The published text of the regulation as it appears in the EU's Official Journal", "An academic article reviewing the regulation's expected impact across affected sectors", "A press release from the Commission summarising the regulation's main provisions"], a: 1, e: "A primary source is the original document itself. News analyses, press releases, and academic reviews are secondary." },
    { i: "1.2.7", c: "1.2", t: "Chart deception", d: 2, q: "A chart shows a 'spectacular' rise in cases. Which feature should make you most cautious before drawing conclusions?", o: ["A single highlighted bar drawn in a brighter colour than the others on the same chart", "A y-axis that starts well above zero without a clear break indicator near the baseline", "A chart shared as a PDF rather than an interactive image embedded in the source page", "Data points plotted as circular markers instead of squares or another distinctive shape"], a: 1, e: "A truncated y-axis without a break indicator can visually exaggerate small differences. Colour, format, and marker style are stylistic, not deceptive in themselves." },
    { i: "1.2.8", c: "1.2", t: "Bias vs hallucination", d: 3, q: "An AI résumé screener consistently rates equally qualified male candidates higher than female ones. This is most accurately described as:", o: ["A hallucination, because the screener policy output is factually wrong about candidate quality", "A bias, reflecting skews in the training data or model that affect group-level outcomes", "A prompt injection, since the input forces the screener into an unintended behaviour", "A jailbreak, since the screener is producing content that violates its safety controls"], a: 1, e: "Bias is systematic, patterned skew in outputs reflecting training-data or design choices. A hallucination is a fabricated fact, not a systematic group-level error." },
    { i: "1.3.1", c: "1.3", t: "Backup 3-2-1", d: 1, q: "The widely recommended '3-2-1' backup rule means:", o: ["Three full backups taken each day, two stored in the cloud, and one on a single USB stick", "Three copies of the data, held on two different media types, with one stored off-site", "Three minutes between automatic saves, two folders for working files, and one named owner", "Three authorised users for the data, two layered passwords, and one administrator account"], a: 1, e: "3-2-1 = three total copies, on at least two different media types, with at least one stored off-site. It protects against device failure, ransomware, and physical disasters." },
    { i: "1.3.2", c: "1.3", t: "Cloud trade-offs", d: 1, q: "Which of the following is NOT a recognised advantage of cloud storage over purely local storage?", o: ["Access from multiple devices regardless of which one created the file in the first place", "Built-in redundancy across multiple data centres operated by the cloud provider in the region", "Guaranteed technical independence from any third-party access to the underlying storage layer", "Easier collaboration through link-sharing with internal and external colleagues on the same file"], a: 2, e: "Cloud storage relies on a third-party provider, who has technical access to the underlying systems and may be subject to legal requests." },
    { i: "1.3.3", c: "1.3", t: "EXIF metadata", d: 2, q: "You take a photo on your phone and email it to a colleague. What hidden information may travel with the file?", o: ["The timestamp the photo was taken, but no other technical data about the camera or its settings", "EXIF metadata, which can include GPS coordinates, the device model, and the date and time", "The phone's IMEI number, the SIM identifier, and the carrier ID, embedded by the camera firmware", "The recipient's network IP address, written into the file when the message is sent"], a: 1, e: "Photos typically embed EXIF metadata: device model, settings, date/time, and (if location services were enabled) GPS coordinates. Stripping EXIF before sharing is good practice for sensitive photos." },
    { i: "1.3.4", c: "1.3", t: "Datafication", d: 2, q: "DigComp 2.2 introduces 'datafication awareness' — the recognition that:", o: ["Data is best stored as numbers so it can be analysed quickly across organisations and platforms", "Everyday digital activity generates data that organisations can collect, analyse, and exploit", "Datafication is unlawful under GDPR because routine activity data identifies individuals", "Only governments collect personal data; commercial platforms operate under different rules"], a: 1, e: "Datafication describes how routine digital interactions (clicks, locations, voice queries) are turned into datasets. It is not inherently illegal but raises questions GDPR seeks to address." },
    { i: "1.3.5", c: "1.3", t: "File naming", d: 1, q: "Which file-naming convention is best for a shared archive used over many years?", o: ["report final FINAL v3 (use this).docx — flagged so colleagues see it as the authoritative copy", "2024-03-15_asylum-policy-report_v02.docx — ISO date, topic, version, with no spaces or marks", "Asylum Report (Maria's copy).docx — author tagging makes ownership clear under the team's filing policy", "report.docx — the simplest name keeps the archive easy to scan and navigate at a glance"], a: 1, e: "ISO-style date prefix, descriptive content, and version number give chronological sortability and unambiguous identification." },
    { i: "1.3.6", c: "1.3", t: "Open data", d: 2, q: "A dataset is described as 'open data'. The defining requirement is that:", o: ["The dataset is free to download from the host's public website, with no account or login needed", "The dataset is published under a licence that permits reuse, redistribution, and modification", "The dataset contains no personal data and so falls outside the scope of data-protection rules", "The dataset is hosted on the systems of a public authority, indexed by topic, rather than a private firm"], a: 1, e: "'Open' refers to the licence — reuse, redistribution and modification must be permitted. Free access alone is not enough; many freely viewable datasets are still copyrighted." },
    { i: "1.3.7", c: "1.3", t: "Cache vs cookies", d: 2, q: "Which best distinguishes a browser cache from cookies?", o: ["Cache stores local resource copies for speed, while cookies store state and identity for sessions", "Cache is encrypted by the browser at rest, while cookies travel and are stored without encryption", "Cache is held server-side by the website, while cookies are stored client-side by the browser only", "Cache and cookies are essentially the same browser-managed mechanism, named differently by vendor"], a: 0, e: "Cache holds local copies of fetched resources to speed up repeat loads. Cookies are small data items used to maintain login state, preferences, and (often) tracking identifiers." },
    { i: "1.3.8", c: "1.3", t: "Permissions check", d: 1, q: "You are about to upload sensitive draft policy notes to a shared team folder. The most important first check is:", o: ["Whether the folder has a recognisable colour icon so it can be picked out at a glance later", "Who has access to the folder and at what permission level before the draft notes are uploaded", "The size of the file relative to the team's quota on the shared drive in the relevant region", "Whether the file name contains spaces or special characters that could cause linking issues"], a: 1, e: "Verifying access scope and permissions prevents inadvertent disclosure to people who should not see drafts. Visual cues like icons are not authoritative." },
    { i: "2.1.1", c: "2.1", t: "Channel choice", d: 1, q: "You need to deliberate carefully with five colleagues across three time zones on a complex policy text. Which channel is most appropriate as the main forum?", o: ["A weekly video call scheduled at 22:00 for some colleagues and 09:00 for the others on the team", "An asynchronous shared document with structured comment threads accessible to all collaborators", "A long single-thread email reply-all chain that captures every contribution in chronological order", "A series of brief instant messages routed through a group chat that the team checks all day long"], a: 1, e: "Asynchronous, structured collaboration suits complex deliberation across time zones — it respects working hours and lets each contributor reflect." },
    { i: "2.1.2", c: "2.1", t: "Sync vs async", d: 1, q: "Which task is best handled synchronously rather than asynchronously?", o: ["Reviewing a 40-page draft report that the team needs feedback on by the end of the working week", "Recording a one-hour briefing for absent colleagues to watch when they return to their desks", "Reaching a short urgent decision that needs two-way clarification within the next ten minutes", "Compiling translation suggestions across the team's working languages over the course of a week"], a: 2, e: "Synchronous communication is preferable when interactivity and quick clarification are essential. Document review, recordings, and multi-day compilation are paradigm asynchronous tasks." },
    { i: "2.1.3", c: "2.1", t: "AI meeting assistant", d: 2, q: "Your office introduces an AI meeting-assistant that transcribes and summarises calls. What is the most important professional consideration before using it on a sensitive call?", o: ["Whether the assistant integrates cleanly with your calendar and meeting-room booking system", "Whether participants are informed and consenting, and the data flow respects data-protection rules", "Whether the tool can render meeting summaries in each participant's preferred working language", "Whether the assistant offers a dark-mode interface for late evening or early morning meetings"], a: 1, e: "Transparency, consent, and compliance are decisive — particularly when calls contain personal or confidential data. Convenience features are secondary." },
    { i: "2.1.4", c: "2.1", t: "Bandwidth issue", d: 2, q: "During a video call, audio is clear but participants' video freezes. The likely bottleneck is:", o: ["Insufficient bandwidth on the network connection", "Encryption overhead", "An out-of-date browser", "Time-zone mismatch"], a: 0, e: "Video streams demand much more bandwidth than audio. Video freezes first when bandwidth is tight, while audio (smaller, prioritised) remains clear." },
    { i: "2.1.5", c: "2.1", t: "Hybrid inclusion", d: 2, q: "A hybrid team meets weekly with some staff in the room and some remote. Which practice best supports inclusion of remote participants?", o: ["Use a single shared microphone in the room so the in-person discussion stays natural and quick", "Have each participant join from their own device, with a chair facilitating turns across rooms", "Ask remote participants to send their questions by email after the meeting closes for the week", "Limit remote participants to listening only and channel decisions through the in-room attendees"], a: 1, e: "'One person, one tile' on the call equalises presence and audibility. Centralised mics tend to favour in-room voices." },
    { i: "2.1.6", c: "2.1", t: "Email vs chat", d: 1, q: "Which message is best sent by email rather than instant chat?", o: ["A formal communication of a final decision that needs to be archived in the relevant case file", "A quick 'Are you free at 3?' message confirming a short slot for an unscheduled call this afternoon", "A reaction to a colleague's joke that is currently winding through a friendly thread in team chat", "A reminder asking the team to check a shared folder for an updated draft in the next minute or so"], a: 0, e: "Email is the appropriate channel for formal, archivable communications and decisions that need a durable record." },
    { i: "2.1.7", c: "2.1", t: "Sensitive data on chat", d: 2, q: "You receive a chat message with confidential personal data of an applicant. The professional response is to:", o: ["Reply on the same chat using only first names so that direct identifiers are removed from the thread", "Continue the discussion on chat because most enterprise chat platforms are encrypted and private by design", "Move the discussion to an authorised, more secure channel and stop sharing identifiable data on the chat", "Forward the chat to your personal email so you can keep a private copy in case the channel is deleted"], a: 2, e: "Personal data should be processed only via authorised, secured channels. Forwarding to personal email creates a new uncontrolled processing instance and a potential GDPR breach." },
    { i: "2.1.8", c: "2.1", t: "Out-of-office", d: 1, q: "What information should an out-of-office auto-reply NOT include?", o: ["Your expected return date, the date your absence began, and a follow-up window for the sender", "An alternative contact who handles urgent matters during your absence and can step in promptly", "Your detailed travel itinerary, hotel address, and personal mobile number for after-hours reach", "A brief acknowledgement of receipt to confirm the original message arrived in your inbox"], a: 2, e: "Auto-replies are sent to anyone, including senders you do not know. Detailed itineraries and personal numbers are over-disclosures and can be misused." },
    { i: "2.2.1", c: "2.2", t: "To/Cc/Bcc", d: 1, q: "You must email a draft briefing to twelve external experts who do not know each other. Which addressing approach best protects their personal data while still allowing replies?", o: ["To: all experts", "Bcc: all experts; To: yourself", "Cc: all experts", "Bcc: yourself; To: all experts"], a: 1, e: "Putting recipients in Bcc prevents disclosure of their email addresses to one another — emails are personal data. Putting yourself in To gives the message a valid To: header without exposing the others." },
    { i: "2.2.2", c: "2.2", t: "Anyone-with-link", d: 2, q: "You share a cloud document via 'Anyone with the link can edit'. What is the principal risk?", o: ["The document loads more slowly, since anonymous viewers consume shared bandwidth, storage, and CPU", "Anyone who obtains the link by forwarding, screenshot, or browser history can edit it without an audit trail", "The document size will be capped, because open-link sharing limits attachments and embedded media inside the file", "The document cannot be opened on mobile devices, since open-link mode disables the platform's mobile clients"], a: 1, e: "Open-link permissions transfer access to anyone who acquires the link, with no audit trail of who viewed or edited." },
    { i: "2.2.3", c: "2.2", t: "Attribution", d: 1, q: "You quote a paragraph from a colleague's report in an internal newsletter. The minimum professional practice is to:", o: ["Reword the paragraph slightly, change a few words, and reuse it without a direct citation in the newsletter", "Cite the author, the report title, and the date of the original publication alongside the quoted text", "Ask the IT department to confirm whether the newsletter platform allows quoted content from internal documents", "Strip the quotation marks, blend the text into the newsletter, and credit the team rather than the original author"], a: 1, e: "Attribution is required regardless of medium. Slight rewording without attribution is plagiarism. IT permission is unrelated to authorship credit." },
    { i: "2.2.4", c: "2.2", t: "Restricted material", d: 2, q: "A colleague forwards you an email marked 'Restricted' from a third party. The appropriate action is to:", o: ["Forward it onward to colleagues you think have a clear interest in the content of the message", "Hold it without redistributing and check whether the original sender authorised wider sharing", "Print a copy and leave it in the team kitchen so colleagues can read it during their own breaks", "Reply-all to ask which other distribution lists the sender intended to include in the original"], a: 1, e: "Restricted markings indicate restricted distribution. Forwarding without authorisation breaches the originator's instruction." },
    { i: "2.2.5", c: "2.2", t: "Expiring links", d: 2, q: "What is a privacy benefit of using time-limited or expiring share links rather than permanent ones?", o: ["They reduce the file size by trimming embedded metadata when the link is generated", "They cannot be opened on mobile devices, narrowing the audience to desktop users", "They limit the window of exposure if the link leaks or is forwarded outside the team", "They make the file public for the link's lifetime, which simplifies access management"], a: 2, e: "An expiring link bounds the period during which a leaked or forwarded link remains exploitable." },
    { i: "2.2.6", c: "2.2", t: "Version control", d: 2, q: "A team is co-authoring a report. Which approach minimises lost edits and confusion?", o: ["Each contributor keeps a personal copy and emails the latest version back and forth as the work progresses", "A single source-of-truth document with built-in version history and named co-editors collaborates on it", "A printed master copy held by the lead author with revisions handwritten and entered in batches", "Paragraphs from each contributor's separate copy are combined into a single document at the end"], a: 1, e: "A live, version-controlled document with named editors avoids fork-and-merge problems entirely. Email round-trips are where edits get lost." },
    { i: "2.2.7", c: "2.2", t: "Reply-all etiquette", d: 1, q: "You are added to a 200-person internal mailing list. You disagree with one message. The most appropriate response is to:", o: ["Reply-all so the entire mailing list sees the view, the reasoning, and the rebuttal in context", "Reply only to the original sender, or raise the point through the appropriate moderated channel", "Forward the disagreement to your manager, copy the list, and let the chain take its own course", "Unsubscribe from the list, ignore the message, and let the original disagreement settle on its own"], a: 1, e: "Reply-all on large lists creates noise and notification cascades. A direct reply keeps the discussion proportionate." },
    { i: "2.2.8", c: "2.2", t: "Citing AI outputs", d: 3, q: "You incorporate a paragraph from a generative-AI chatbot into a report. The most professionally responsible approach is to:", o: ["Cite the AI as a named co-author so credit and accountability for the paragraph are recorded", "Disclose the AI use under your organisation's policy and verify factual claims independently", "Omit any mention of the AI use because the tool is too unreliable to count as a real source", "Quote the passage in the report unattributed if the wording sounds plausible to a domain reader"], a: 1, e: "Disclose-and-verify is the emerging professional norm and is consistent with most organisational AI policies. AI outputs lack authorship in the legal/academic sense." },
    { i: "2.3.1", c: "2.3", t: "eIDAS", d: 2, q: "What is the principal purpose of the EU's eIDAS framework?", o: ["To deploy free Wi-Fi in public buildings under the WiFi4EU initiative across Member States", "To enable secure cross-border electronic identification and trust services within the EU", "To replace national identity cards with a single EU-issued physical identity card for citizens", "To regulate user-generated content on large social-media platforms operating inside the EU"], a: 1, e: "eIDAS (Reg. 910/2014, updated 2024) sets EU-wide rules for electronic identification and trust services so that an e-signature recognised in one Member State is recognised in others." },
    { i: "2.3.2", c: "2.3", t: "ECI", d: 1, q: "The European Citizens' Initiative is best described as:", o: ["A petition mechanism letting citizens invite the Commission to propose legislation if thresholds are met", "A binding cross-border referendum allowing citizens to enact EU-wide legislation by direct popular vote", "A consumer-complaint platform that channels disputes about goods and services to the relevant agencies", "A grant scheme that funds civil-society organisations campaigning on EU policy issues across Member States"], a: 0, e: "The ECI lets at least one million citizens from a minimum number of Member States invite the Commission to make a legislative proposal. It is non-binding." },
    { i: "2.3.3", c: "2.3", t: "Astroturfing", d: 2, q: "A 'grassroots' online campaign turns out to have been organised and paid for by a single corporate sponsor while presenting itself as spontaneous citizen action. This practice is called:", o: ["Trolling", "Astroturfing", "Lobbying", "Whistleblowing"], a: 1, e: "Astroturfing fakes grassroots support to manipulate public discourse. Lobbying is openly representing an interest; trolling is disruptive online behaviour; whistleblowing exposes wrongdoing." },
    { i: "2.3.4", c: "2.3", t: "Digital inclusion", d: 2, q: "A municipal service moves to 'digital by default'. Which step best addresses the digital-inclusion risk?", o: ["Removing all paper processes immediately so citizens are nudged into adopting the digital channel quickly", "Maintaining alternative channels (phone, in-person) and offering digital-skills support for those who need it", "Charging a small administrative fee for the paper channel so the digital channel becomes the cheaper option", "Limiting the digital service to standard working hours so it operates on the same schedule as in-person service"], a: 1, e: "Digital-by-default works only if no-one is excluded. Maintaining alternative channels and skills support is consistent with the EU Digital Decade target." },
    { i: "2.3.5", c: "2.3", t: "Have Your Say", d: 1, q: "You want to provide formal input on a draft EU regulation. The official channel is:", o: ["Posting on social media", "The 'Have Your Say' portal on the Commission's website", "Sending an email to any random EU institution", "Calling Europe Direct"], a: 1, e: "'Have Your Say' is the Commission's public-consultation portal. Social-media posts are not formal input; Europe Direct is for general information requests." },
    { i: "2.3.6", c: "2.3", t: "eID security", d: 2, q: "A national eID card lets a citizen log in to a public-service portal. What is the typical security model?", o: ["A single static password is stored on the card chip and matched by the portal at login", "Two-factor authentication: possession of the card plus knowledge of a PIN, read via reader or NFC", "Biometric authentication alone, with the citizen's fingerprint replacing both card and PIN", "No authentication occurs — the card simply discloses the citizen's identity to the portal"], a: 1, e: "eID schemes generally rely on possession of the card and knowledge of a PIN — a classic two-factor model — with cryptographic certificates on the card." },
    { i: "2.3.7", c: "2.3", t: "Open government data", d: 1, q: "Why does the EU promote open public-sector data?", o: ["So that statistical offices, archives, and registries can be replaced by open portals under a single policy", "So that transparency, reuse for innovation, and accountability are enabled across the public sector", "So that databases can be released without applying personal-data rules, since the data are now public", "So that running data centres becomes cheaper than the archives, even when adjusted for upkeep over time"], a: 1, e: "The Open Data Directive (2019/1024) frames open public-sector data as a driver of transparency, innovation and accountability — distinct from GDPR obligations." },
    { i: "2.3.8", c: "2.3", t: "Computational propaganda", d: 3, q: "A coordinated network of automated accounts amplifies a single hashtag to make a fringe view appear mainstream. The most precise label is:", o: ["Targeted advertising", "Computational propaganda using bots / inauthentic coordinated behaviour", "Search engine optimisation", "Content moderation"], a: 1, e: "Computational propaganda — algorithmic amplification, often via bots and coordinated inauthentic behaviour — is a recognised category in EU disinformation policy." },
    { i: "2.4.1", c: "2.4", t: "Track changes", d: 1, q: "In a long collaborative document, what is the main professional advantage of using 'track changes' (revision marks)?", o: ["It reduces the file size by storing only the differences between successive draft versions, every time", "It produces a transparent, attributable trail of every edit that collaborators can accept or reject", "It encrypts the document so only authorised collaborators can view the proposed changes", "It removes formatting differences between contributors so the final document looks consistent"], a: 1, e: "Track changes makes authorship of edits explicit and reversible — essential for collaborative legal or policy drafting." },
    { i: "2.4.2", c: "2.4", t: "Comments vs edits", d: 2, q: "During review, you want to suggest a wording change without altering the master text. The most appropriate tool is:", o: ["A comment (or suggestion mode)", "Direct in-line editing", "A separate email", "A printed annotation"], a: 0, e: "Comments and suggestion modes propose changes that the author can accept or reject. Direct edits without consent overwrite authorship." },
    { i: "2.4.3", c: "2.4", t: "Merge conflicts", d: 1, q: "What is the main risk if two people work on the same offline copy of a Word document simultaneously and email versions back and forth?", o: ["Default fonts will be substituted on receipt and the document layout will shift across the versions", "Edits by one person may, depending on merge order, overwrite the other's edits or simply be lost", "The document may, in some setups, become encrypted automatically when sent through corporate mail filters", "The file size will roughly double each time the document is exchanged between collaborators"], a: 1, e: "Without a single source of truth, parallel offline edits create merge conflicts and lost work. Live co-editing avoids this." },
    { i: "2.4.4", c: "2.4", t: "Kanban WIP limits", d: 2, q: "Your team uses a Kanban board. The 'work-in-progress' (WIP) limit on a column is intended to:", o: ["Push everyone to work faster by setting a daily quota that the column shows the team is missing", "Prevent overload by capping concurrent tasks in a column, making bottlenecks visible to the team", "Encrypt the board so only authorised team members can see in-progress work and pending tasks", "Hide tasks from external viewers so the board is suitable for showing during stakeholder demos"], a: 1, e: "WIP limits are a core Kanban discipline. By capping in-progress work they make bottlenecks visible and reduce context-switching." },
    { i: "2.4.5", c: "2.4", t: "Whiteboards for ideation", d: 1, q: "For an early-stage brainstorming session with a hybrid team, the most suitable tool is:", o: ["A formal Word document", "A shared online whiteboard with sticky notes", "A printed agenda", "A spreadsheet"], a: 1, e: "Whiteboards support visual, non-linear, low-friction ideation and let everyone contribute simultaneously." },
    { i: "2.4.6", c: "2.4", t: "Hybrid norms", d: 2, q: "Which working agreement most reduces friction in a hybrid team?", o: ["Meet in person whenever possible so the collaboration usually retains the richness of physical presence", "Set explicit camera norms for discussion vs status and record decisions in writing for absent colleagues", "Forbid asynchronous decisions to keep everyone in sync on the same day and the same shared timeline", "Require everyone to be online from 9 to 17 across all time zones so simultaneous availability is granted"], a: 1, e: "Explicit norms about when to use which channel, and durable written records of decisions, are documented best practice for hybrid working in DigComp 2.2's Annex 3." },
    { i: "2.4.7", c: "2.4", t: "AI in collaboration", d: 3, q: "You and a colleague co-author a brief using a generative-AI assistant. Which practice is most aligned with DigComp 2.2 guidance on AI-supported collaboration?", o: ["Each co-author uses the AI privately, drafts in isolation, and the merged outputs go in without discussion", "The team agrees up front how the AI will be used, records that use, and checks the factual content together", "The AI takes the editorial decisions, sets the tone, and chooses structure so the brief reads as one voice", "The team relies on the AI, keeps no record of its use, and presents the brief as ordinary single-author work"], a: 1, e: "Team-level transparency, documentation, and human verification are the governance-aligned approach. Hidden use undermines trust and accountability." },
    { i: "2.4.8", c: "2.4", t: "Permissions hygiene", d: 2, q: "A team wiki has accumulated dozens of editor accounts over years, including for people who have left. The best hygiene practice is:", o: ["Leave the dormant accounts in place so the wiki preserves a historical record of past contributors", "Review access periodically and revoke editor rights for departed or long-inactive users on the wiki", "Add more editors so the wiki stays active and the dormant accounts blend into the wider editor list", "Switch the wiki to public-edit so editor-level accounts no longer matter for who can change content"], a: 1, e: "Periodic access review (joiner-mover-leaver) is a basic security and information-governance control — abandoned accounts are common breach vectors." },
    { i: "2.5.1", c: "2.5", t: "All caps", d: 1, q: "A short message in ALL CAPS sent in a professional chat is generally interpreted as:", o: ["Important and urgent in a neutral way", "Shouting or anger", "A formatting error", "A foreign-language quotation"], a: 1, e: "Online netiquette has long treated all-caps as shouting. For emphasis, use bold or italics; for urgency, say so explicitly." },
    { i: "2.5.2", c: "2.5", t: "Intercultural", d: 2, q: "You are working with colleagues across many EU countries. Which practice best supports respectful intercultural communication?", o: ["Use idioms from your own language for colour, lean on cultural references, and rely on context cues", "Prefer plain, literal language; clarify acronyms on first use; and stay patient with non-native speakers", "Speak louder on calls, repeat key phrases, and add background context so the message reaches everyone", "Avoid emoji entirely on calls and in chat, even when the rest of the team uses them across the day"], a: 1, e: "Plain language and explicit acronyms are pillars of inclusive professional communication, especially in multilingual EU contexts." },
    { i: "2.5.3", c: "2.5", t: "Bystander response", d: 2, q: "You witness a colleague being personally attacked in a public team channel. The professionally appropriate response is to:", o: ["Stay out of it, observe the exchange, and let the participants resolve the disagreement themselves", "Privately support the colleague, avoid amplifying the attack, and report through the proper channel", "Reply in the same channel with a sharp counter-message, name the attacker, and call out the behaviour", "Screenshot the exchange, post it on social media, and tag colleagues so the wider community sees it"], a: 1, e: "Bystander best practice is to support the target, avoid amplifying the abuse, and use formal reporting channels." },
    { i: "2.5.4", c: "2.5", t: "Inclusive salutations", d: 1, q: "Which is an example of inclusive professional written communication?", o: ["Addressing a mixed group as 'Dear Sirs' to keep the salutation short and traditional in tone", "Addressing a group as 'Dear colleagues' or 'Dear all' to greet the recipients equally and clearly", "Using only first names to keep the message informal and to set a friendly working tone right away", "Avoiding any salutation entirely so the message goes straight to the substance without preamble"], a: 1, e: "Gender-neutral, role-appropriate salutations are inclusive defaults. 'Dear Sirs' assumes a single gender." },
    { i: "2.5.5", c: "2.5", t: "Accessible posts", d: 2, q: "You publish an internal social post containing an infographic with key figures. Which practice supports accessibility?", o: ["Post the image alone since visual infographics communicate the key figures faster than written text", "Add alternative text describing the figures and include the key data in the post text alongside it", "Use bright primary colours throughout the infographic to make the figures pop on a busy team feed", "Post the infographic as a screenshot of the original image to keep the post and the file-size small"], a: 1, e: "Alt-text and an accompanying text version make content perceivable to screen-reader users and to anyone whose images do not load — a WCAG 2.2 baseline expectation." },
    { i: "2.5.6", c: "2.5", t: "Emoji register", d: 1, q: "In a formal letter to an external authority, the appropriate use of emoji is:", o: ["Liberal use throughout the letter so the tone reads as friendly and approachable to the reader", "Reserved or absent so the correspondence follows the conventional formal written register", "Required at the start of each paragraph so each section opens with a clear visual marker", "Restricted to the opening salutation as a single decorative element near the top of the letter"], a: 1, e: "Register matters. Emoji are typical in chat and informal messages; formal correspondence with authorities follows conventional written norms." },
    { i: "2.5.7", c: "2.5", t: "Public posts as staff", d: 2, q: "You post a strongly-worded political opinion on your personal social-media account. As an EU staff member, the most prudent consideration is:", o: ["Personal accounts are entirely separate from professional duties under EU staff regulations", "Public posts can still be linked to your role and engage your institution's duty of reserve", "Public posts are safe as long as account privacy settings restrict them to your contacts", "Free speech protections under the Charter exempt staff from any professional consequence"], a: 1, e: "Staff regulations in EU institutions include duties of loyalty and discretion; public posts are seldom truly 'private'. Codes of conduct often address external statements." },
    { i: "2.5.8", c: "2.5", t: "Right to disconnect", d: 2, q: "A colleague messages you outside working hours and demands a reply because the chat shows you 'online'. The appropriate professional norm is to:", o: ["Reply right away whatever the hour, since being shown online amounts to an availability signal", "Treat the right to disconnect as the default and reply during working hours unless a real emergency", "Switch your chat status to invisible from now on, so questions of availability typically never arise", "Reply with a single emoji acknowledgement so the colleague knows the message was at least seen"], a: 1, e: "The right to disconnect (recognised in DigComp 2.2's RW examples) protects rest periods. Genuine emergencies are an exception, not the default." },
    { i: "2.6.1", c: "2.6", t: "Active vs passive footprint", d: 2, q: "Which is an example of a PASSIVE digital footprint?", o: ["A blog post you publish", "Tracking cookies that record your browsing patterns without explicit posting", "An email you send", "A photo you upload"], a: 1, e: "Active footprints come from intentional posts and contributions. Passive footprints are generated by tools observing you (cookies, telemetry, location data) often without conscious action." },
    { i: "2.6.2", c: "2.6", t: "Right to erasure", d: 2, q: "Under GDPR Article 17 ('right to erasure'), a data subject may request deletion of their personal data when:", o: ["A request is submitted, and the controller must satisfy it without further policy or legal conditions", "The data are no longer needed for the original purpose, or consent is withdrawn, with exceptions", "The data are factually inaccurate, the controller refuses to correct them, and an audit confirms the error", "The data are processed for direct marketing, automated profiling, and special-category Article 9 purposes"], a: 1, e: "Article 17 lists specific grounds (no longer necessary, consent withdrawn, unlawful processing) and explicit exceptions (e.g. freedom of expression, legal obligation). It is not absolute." },
    { i: "2.6.3", c: "2.6", t: "Inferred personal data", d: 3, q: "A platform infers from your activity that you may be pregnant — even though you never disclosed it. Under GDPR, this inferred information is:", o: ["Not personal data, since you never directly provided this information to the platform yourself", "Personal data, and may rise to special-category health data depending on the surrounding context", "Outside GDPR scope, since the data are typically governed by the platform's own data-use policy", "Treated as public information once the platform has produced it from observable activity signals"], a: 1, e: "Inferred and observed data about an identifiable person are personal data. Health-related inferences engage Article 9 special-category protections." },
    { i: "2.6.4", c: "2.6", t: "SSO trade-off", d: 2, q: "You sign in to many services using a single 'Login with X' provider. The main trade-off is:", o: ["Sign-in is consistently faster than entering a password, which is the principal benefit", "Fewer passwords to manage, against concentrated risk and cross-site profiling by the provider", "Lower battery use because the device handles fewer authentication round-trips per session", "Stronger encryption of the stored credential than a service-specific password manager offers"], a: 1, e: "SSO reduces password reuse and friction but consolidates a high-value target and shares identity signals with the provider." },
    { i: "2.6.5", c: "2.6", t: "Personas", d: 2, q: "You maintain a professional LinkedIn profile and a separate gaming-community pseudonym. This is best described as managing:", o: ["Two separate legal identities recognised distinctly under national identity-document rules and tax law", "Multiple digital personas linked to one underlying identity, with different audiences and disclosures", "Two unrelated accounts that are legally invisible to one another and to the platforms hosting them", "A practice that breaches GDPR because creating a pseudonym constitutes processing personal data"], a: 1, e: "Maintaining context-appropriate personas is normal digital-identity practice. The accounts can still be legally and technically linked." },
    { i: "2.6.6", c: "2.6", t: "Self-audit", d: 1, q: "Old, embarrassing posts surface during a job application. A reasonable proactive practice is to:", o: ["Submit search-engine takedown requests, monitor recovery confirmations, and lodge appeals if denied", "Search your own name from time to time, review privacy settings, and prune posts you no longer want", "Delete every social-media account, archive backup copies for legal review, and notify former contacts", "File a privacy claim, request platform takedowns, and instruct the platforms' legal teams to act fast"], a: 1, e: "Self-audit (search yourself, review settings, prune content) is the practical baseline. Erasure rights exist but are bounded." },
    { i: "2.6.7", c: "2.6", t: "Profiling defined", d: 3, q: "Under GDPR, 'profiling' specifically refers to:", o: ["Storing or organising personal data records as part of routine controller activity in a structured filing", "Automated processing that evaluates personal aspects of a person to analyse or predict their behaviour", "Commercial use of personal data for direct-marketing campaigns or advertising on the open web", "Tracking a user's location across websites for analytics, without producing any behavioural inference"], a: 1, e: "Article 4(4) GDPR defines profiling narrowly as automated evaluation of personal aspects. Storage alone is not profiling; profiling has stricter conditions especially when fully automated and producing legal effects (Art 22)." },
    { i: "2.6.8", c: "2.6", t: "Weak security questions", d: 2, q: "A common 'security question' for account recovery is your mother's maiden name. Why is this often a weak control?", o: ["The answer is usually too long for the typical user to remember, leading to written notes nearby", "The answer is often public or socially discoverable, undermining its value as a hidden recovery secret", "Recovery answers should be double-encrypted at rest, and a maiden name does not survive that pipeline", "Most modern browsers cannot autofill the answer, leading to typing errors and account lock-outs"], a: 1, e: "Genealogical and personal-history facts are often publicly inferable, defeating the 'secret' premise. MFA via authenticator app or hardware key is far stronger." },
    { i: "3.1.1", c: "3.1", t: "PDF for fixed layout", d: 1, q: "You need to send a final report that must look identical on every device and operating system. The best format is:", o: [".docx", ".pdf", ".rtf", ".txt"], a: 1, e: "PDF preserves layout, fonts, and pagination across platforms. DOCX is for editable working documents and may render differently." },
    { i: "3.1.2", c: "3.1", t: "SVG for logos", d: 2, q: "Which file format is best for a logo that must scale crisply from a business card to a billboard?", o: [".jpg", ".png", ".svg", ".gif"], a: 2, e: "SVG is vector — it scales without quality loss. JPEG and PNG are raster (pixel-based) and degrade when enlarged." },
    { i: "3.1.3", c: "3.1", t: "JPEG vs PNG", d: 1, q: "JPEG and PNG differ principally because:", o: ["JPEG uses lossy compression suited to photographs, and PNG uses lossless compression with transparency", "PNG predates JPEG and was its predecessor for compliance with the early image standards in the 1990s", "JPEG runs through a plug-in layer, and modern browsers tend to fall back to PNG when it is unavailable", "PNG handles only icons and small interface graphics, and JPEG handles photographs and large images"], a: 0, e: "JPEG uses lossy compression and is well-suited to photographs. PNG is lossless and supports an alpha (transparency) channel — preferred for screenshots, line art." },
    { i: "3.1.4", c: "3.1", t: "Slide accessibility", d: 2, q: "You are creating a presentation slide deck. Which practice contributes MOST to accessibility from the start?", o: ["Use bright primary colours, dense layouts, and tight margins so each slide reads from the back of the room", "Add alt-text to images, use built-in heading styles, and check colour contrast on every slide", "Pick an unusual decorative font for titles, vary it across the deck, and use it for body text as well", "Animate every slide transition, add motion to bullet reveals, and play sound so the audience stays engaged"], a: 1, e: "Alt-text, structural styles (so reading order is correct), and adequate contrast align with WCAG 2.2." },
    { i: "3.1.5", c: "3.1", t: "Captions vs subtitles", d: 2, q: "Which is a defining feature of CAPTIONS as distinct from subtitles?", o: ["Captions are always in a different language than the original audio track on the video", "Captions include non-speech audio cues for viewers who are deaf or hard of hearing", "Captions are rendered in a smaller font than subtitles to leave more visible space on screen", "Captions are a decorative overlay rather than a transcription tied to the spoken dialogue"], a: 1, e: "Captions assume the viewer cannot hear the audio and therefore include relevant non-speech sounds. Subtitles assume hearing audiences and translate dialogue." },
    { i: "3.1.6", c: "3.1", t: "AI image disclosure", d: 3, q: "You generate an illustration with a generative-AI image tool and use it in an internal newsletter. The most professionally responsible practice is to:", o: ["Treat the image as a stock asset, run it through the editor's review, and use it across newsletters without comment", "Disclose that the image is AI-generated, comply with the tool's terms, and check for visible artefacts", "Claim the image as your own artwork, retain visual consistency across newsletters, and avoid mentioning the tool", "Add the watermark of a recognised illustrator, attribute the image to that style family, and credit them by name"], a: 1, e: "Disclosure, ToS-compliance, and quality checking are converging best practice; the EU AI Act adds transparency obligations for AI-generated media." },
    { i: "3.1.7", c: "3.1", t: "PST not an image", d: 2, q: "Which file extension is NOT an image format?", o: [".png", ".jpeg", ".pst", ".gif"], a: 2, e: ".PST is a Microsoft Outlook personal-storage file (mailbox archive). PNG, JPEG, and GIF are image formats. This question type appears in the official EPSO sample set." },
    { i: "3.1.8", c: "3.1", t: "PDF accessibility", d: 2, q: "What makes a PDF accessible to screen-reader users?", o: ["A small file size, fast loading, and minimal images so the file works on slow connections and devices", "Tagged structure with headings and reading order, embedded text, and alt-text on every figure", "A clear cover page, a summary of contents, and large readable type so readers can scan the document", "High-resolution images, sharp diagrams, and detailed figures so users can zoom in to read fine print"], a: 1, e: "Untagged or scanned-image PDFs are opaque to assistive technology. Proper tagging and embedded text are core accessibility requirements (and are part of EN 301 549 / WCAG 2.2)." },
    { i: "3.2.1", c: "3.2", t: "Plagiarism", d: 2, q: "You read a paragraph in a published study, change a few words, and use it in your report without attribution. This is:", o: ["Acceptable, because you changed words", "Plagiarism, regardless of word changes", "Original work, because the words are not identical", "Fair use in all cases"], a: 1, e: "Plagiarism is presenting another's ideas or expression as your own. Light paraphrase without attribution remains plagiarism." },
    { i: "3.2.2", c: "3.2", t: "TASL", d: 1, q: "You combine three CC-BY photos into a collage for a public report. The minimum requirement is to:", o: ["Use the photos directly, list the source platform once in the report, and proceed without per-image credit", "Credit each photographer with title where available, author, source, and licence (TASL convention)", "Email the original photographers, request fresh permission, and wait for written approval before publication", "Convert each photo to a public-domain dedication, drop the credits, and publish the collage unattributed"], a: 1, e: "CC-BY requires attribution. The TASL convention (Title, Author, Source, Licence) is the practical attribution standard." },
    { i: "3.2.3", c: "3.2", t: "ND derivatives", d: 2, q: "You translate a CC-BY-ND article. This is:", o: ["Generally allowed because attribution covers the licence requirements for any reuse of the article", "Generally not allowed without separate permission because ND prohibits derivative works of the original", "Generally allowed if you also share the translation under the same Creative Commons licence terms", "Generally allowed if you publish the translation without listing the original author's name"], a: 1, e: "ND = NoDerivatives. A translation is a derivative work and is not permitted by CC-BY-ND. CC-BY (without ND) and CC-BY-SA permit translations." },
    { i: "3.2.4", c: "3.2", t: "AI re-use", d: 3, q: "You ask a generative-AI tool to draft a section for your report. Before integrating it, the most rigorous step is:", o: ["Paste the draft directly, run it through the team's editing pass, and adjust the wording during review", "Check factual claims against authoritative sources, edit for accuracy, and disclose the AI use upfront", "Translate the draft into another working language, retranslate it back, and use the result as a sanity check", "Mark each AI passage with quotation marks, label it in the byline, and credit the model as a contributor"], a: 1, e: "AI outputs are starting points: they require fact-checking, editorial integration, and disclosure consistent with organisational policy." },
    { i: "3.2.5", c: "3.2", t: "Mashup risk", d: 2, q: "What is a key legal risk when creating a 'mashup' of music tracks and publishing it?", o: ["File size grows large enough to breach the platform's upload limit and the user's own storage quota", "Source tracks are copyright-protected, and the mashup is likely to count as an infringing derivative", "Mashups cannot be played on most mobile devices because of codec incompatibility with the source tracks", "Audio quality drops below the minimum required by the streaming platform's publication guidelines"], a: 1, e: "Even for non-commercial mashups, multiple layers of copyright (composition, performance, recording) usually apply. Licences or specific exceptions are needed." },
    { i: "3.2.6", c: "3.2", t: "ShareAlike", d: 1, q: "In an adapted version of a CC-BY-SA work, which is required?", o: ["Attribution to the original author and release of the adaptation under the same or a compatible CC-BY-SA licence", "Removing the original author's name from the adaptation so the new work stands as a fully independent piece", "Releasing the adaptation as proprietary so the rights to redistribute belong to whoever made the changes", "Charging a fee for downstream reuse to recover the cost of producing the adaptation from the source"], a: 0, e: "SA = ShareAlike: derivatives must be released under the same or a compatible licence. Attribution remains mandatory in all CC licences (except CC0)." },
    { i: "3.2.7", c: "3.2", t: "Embed vs copy", d: 2, q: "Which use of a YouTube video is generally lowest in copyright risk for an internal blog post?", o: ["Downloading the video file and re-uploading it to your team's internal video hosting service", "Embedding the official YouTube player using the provided code so it streams from the original source", "Cropping a few seconds of the video and reposting the clip with a credit line in the caption", "Recording the screen while the video plays and saving that capture as the post's hero asset"], a: 1, e: "Embedding the official player respects the platform's intended distribution and the rights-holder's controls. Downloading and re-uploading is typically infringing." },
    { i: "3.2.8", c: "3.2", t: "Translation rights", d: 3, q: "Translating a copyright-protected book without permission and posting the translation online is generally:", o: ["Permitted under fair use in all jurisdictions because translations exist as separate creative works", "An infringement of the author's exclusive right to authorise translations as a derivative work", "Allowed because the translation is itself a creative act that produces a new work distinct from the source", "Allowed provided the translation is offered free of charge with no commercial revenue from the posting"], a: 1, e: "The right to authorise translations is part of copyright. Without permission or a relevant exception, public posting of an unauthorised translation is infringing." },
    { i: "3.3.1", c: "3.3", t: "CC vs copyright", d: 2, q: "Creative Commons licences are best described as:", o: ["An alternative to copyright that abolishes it, releasing creative works directly into the public domain", "Licences built on top of copyright that pre-authorise certain uses by anyone receiving the work", "A legal exemption from copyright introduced by EU directives that applies across the single market", "A trademark scheme that lets creators register their works under a recognised CC sign or label"], a: 1, e: "CC licences operate within copyright, granting users specific permissions in advance. They do not replace or abolish copyright." },
    { i: "3.3.2", c: "3.3", t: "CC0 vs PDM", d: 3, q: "Which best distinguishes CC0 from the Public Domain Mark (PDM)?", o: ["The two are identical Creative Commons tools and may be applied interchangeably to any work", "CC0 is an active waiver of rights by the holder, while PDM labels work already in the public domain", "PDM is a paid Creative Commons licence administered for the use of institutional rights holders", "CC0 requires attribution to the original author for any reuse of the work to be considered lawful"], a: 1, e: "CC0 is an active waiver/dedication by a rights-holder. PDM is a label asserting that a work is already in the public domain through operation of law." },
    { i: "3.3.3", c: "3.3", t: "NC by use", d: 2, q: "A photo is licensed CC BY-NC. A small charity uses it on a fundraising page that asks for donations. Is this compatible?", o: ["Yes — registered charities typically count as non-commercial by definition, so any use is permitted", "It depends — non-commercial is defined by the use, not the user, and fundraising may count as commercial", "No — charities can never use NC-licensed works because their public status invalidates the licence", "Yes — the BY (attribution) element allows any reuse so long as the original creator is credited"], a: 1, e: "NC is defined by use: 'primarily intended for or directed toward commercial advantage or monetary compensation'. Charity status alone does not exempt the use." },
    { i: "3.3.4", c: "3.3", t: "All CC require BY", d: 1, q: "Which obligation applies to ALL six standard CC licences (CC BY, BY-SA, BY-ND, BY-NC, BY-NC-SA, BY-NC-ND)?", o: ["ShareAlike", "Non-commercial only", "Attribution", "No derivatives"], a: 2, e: "Attribution (BY) is the common element of all six licences. SA, NC and ND apply only to subsets. Only CC0 removes the attribution requirement." },
    { i: "3.3.5", c: "3.3", t: "Free to view ≠ free to reuse", d: 2, q: "You find an essay freely viewable on a personal blog. You want to republish it on your team's intranet. The correct assumption is:", o: ["Free to view on the open web is, in general, equivalent to free to reuse, with no further permission needed", "Reuse requires permission or a licence; visibility on the open web does not by itself grant one", "All content published on the open web automatically falls into the public domain after publication", "Internal reuse on a team intranet is automatically lawful because no external publication occurs"], a: 1, e: "Visibility implies no licence. Reuse needs the rights-holder's permission or an applicable exception. 'Internal' use is still reproduction." },
    { i: "3.3.6", c: "3.3", t: "Open source vs freeware", d: 2, q: "Which best distinguishes open-source software from freeware?", o: ["Open source is always free of cost; freeware always requires a paid commercial licence", "Open source grants rights to study and modify the source code; freeware is gratis but proprietary", "They are the same — both terms describe software released without a paid licence fee", "Freeware automatically becomes open source once it has been distributed to enough users"], a: 1, e: "Open source = freedom to use/study/modify/redistribute the source. Freeware = zero-cost but proprietary, often with no access to source code." },
    { i: "3.3.7", c: "3.3", t: "EU copyright duration", d: 2, q: "In the EU, the standard copyright duration for a literary work is:", o: ["20 years from creation", "Life of the author + 70 years", "Indefinite", "Life of the author + 25 years"], a: 1, e: "Directive 2006/116/EC sets the standard at the life of the author + 70 years for most literary and artistic works." },
    { i: "3.3.8", c: "3.3", t: "TDM exception", d: 3, q: "The 2019 EU Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market introduces a text-and-data-mining (TDM) exception. For commercial actors, this exception is:", o: ["Unconditional, allowing any reuse of mined content for commercial purposes regardless of source", "Conditional on rights-holders not having opted out by machine-readable reservation in advance", "Limited to public-domain works that are no longer subject to copyright protection in the EU", "Restricted to journalism organisations carrying out investigative work in the public interest"], a: 1, e: "Article 4 of Directive 2019/790 lets commercial actors carry out TDM unless rights-holders opt out in an appropriate machine-readable form. Article 3 grants a stronger exception for research organisations." },
    { i: "3.4.1", c: "3.4", t: "Algorithmic thinking", d: 1, q: "Algorithmic thinking is best described as:", o: ["Memorising the syntax of a particular programming language so problems can be encoded directly", "Breaking a problem into a clear sequence of unambiguous steps that can be executed mechanically", "Using a generative-AI assistant to translate a plain-language description into runnable source code", "Buying a faster computer so that the existing solution can finish within an acceptable time budget"], a: 1, e: "Algorithmic thinking is independent of language or tools. It is the capacity to decompose problems into stepwise, executable procedures." },
    { i: "3.4.2", c: "3.4", t: "Loops", d: 1, q: "In a recipe-style algorithm, an instruction like 'while the water is not boiling, keep heating' corresponds to:", o: ["A conditional (if statement)", "A loop with a continuation condition", "A function definition", "A constant"], a: 1, e: "'While X, do Y' is a paradigm loop construct. A conditional executes once if a condition holds; a loop repeats while/until a condition changes." },
    { i: "3.4.3", c: "3.4", t: "Pseudocode", d: 1, q: "Pseudocode is useful primarily because it:", o: ["Runs faster than equivalent compiled code because pseudocode skips intermediate optimisation steps", "Lets you describe an algorithm clearly without committing to a specific programming language's syntax", "Encrypts the algorithm so competing teams cannot reverse-engineer the design from the source code", "Is a required intermediate representation that compilers convert into machine code during the build"], a: 1, e: "Pseudocode communicates logic to humans, language-independently. It is not executable; clarity is its purpose." },
    { i: "3.4.4", c: "3.4", t: "No-code trade-off", d: 2, q: "A 'no-code' workflow tool lets you automate office tasks without programming. The main trade-off versus traditional code is:", o: ["No-code typically runs faster than equivalent code, by margins of 2x, due to platform-level tuning", "No-code is more accessible but less flexible; complex or unusual logic still requires code", "No-code platforms eliminate most bugs because the visual interface prevents common syntax errors", "No-code automations do not need additional testing once the visual flow has been built and saved"], a: 1, e: "No-code platforms accelerate common workflows but constrain expressiveness. Code remains essential for non-standard requirements and fine control." },
    { i: "3.4.5", c: "3.4", t: "AI is designed", d: 2, q: "DigComp 2.2 emphasises that AI systems are 'programmed by humans, with values and biases of their designers'. The practical implication for a citizen is to:", o: ["Trust AI outputs completely because the underlying processing is mathematical and free of human bias", "Appraise AI outputs critically and recognise that behaviour reflects design choices and training data", "Ignore AI tools entirely so that any bias they reflect cannot influence one's own decisions or work", "Treat AI as a neutral oracle whose outputs are factual statements that can be cited without further checks"], a: 1, e: "DigComp 2.2's AI annex stresses that AI is not a neutral oracle. Critical appraisal — including of training data and design intent — is part of citizen-level AI literacy." },
    { i: "3.4.6", c: "3.4", t: "Debugging", d: 1, q: "A simple script does not produce the expected output. The most productive first step is to:", o: ["Rewrite from scratch", "Reproduce the problem reliably and locate the smallest input that triggers it", "Ask a colleague to write it", "Disable error messages"], a: 1, e: "Reliable reproduction and minimisation are the diagnostic foundations. Rewriting often re-introduces bugs; suppressing errors hides information." },
    { i: "3.4.7", c: "3.4", t: "Macros", d: 2, q: "You repeatedly perform a 12-step formatting routine in a spreadsheet. The most efficient automation is:", o: ["Hire someone to do it", "Record or write a macro / script that performs the steps reliably", "Print the spreadsheet", "Use a different colour"], a: 1, e: "Macros and scripts automate deterministic, repeated procedures, freeing time and reducing errors. This is exactly the kind of self-service automation DigComp 3.4 promotes." },
    { i: "3.4.8", c: "3.4", t: "AI code review", d: 3, q: "You ask a generative-AI tool to write a short script. The output runs but produces wrong results in edge cases. Which best describes the situation?", o: ["AI-generated code is correct by construction once the script runs without raising any errors", "AI-generated code needs the same testing and edge-case scrutiny as any human-written contribution", "Edge cases are unimportant in everyday automation since they rarely arise in real input data", "The bug is the user's fault for not specifying the edge case explicitly enough in the prompt"], a: 1, e: "AI-generated code can be plausible-looking yet incorrect, especially for edge cases. Treat it like any other contribution: review, test, validate." },
    { i: "4.1.1", c: "4.1", t: "Smishing", d: 2, q: "You receive a personalised SMS that pretends to be from your bank, with your name and last digits of an account. This is best described as:", o: ["Whaling, the targeted form of phishing aimed at senior executives, board members, or other high-value targets", "Smishing, the SMS variant of phishing, frequently personalised with details like name or account number", "Vishing, the voice-based form of phishing carried out by phone with the attacker on the line", "Spoofing on its own, since the message forges sender identity but does not request information"], a: 1, e: "Smishing = phishing over SMS. Whaling targets executives; vishing is voice-based; spoofing alone refers to forging identity, not the act of soliciting." },
    { i: "4.1.2", c: "4.1", t: "Phishing vs spoofing", d: 3, q: "Spoofing and phishing are related but distinct concepts. Which statement is most accurate?", o: ["Spoofing forges an identity such as an email header, and phishing tricks the target into giving up data", "Synonyms for the same email-fraud technique (such as account takeover) under different industry labels", "Spoofing requires physical hardware tampering on the target's device, and phishing is a software attack", "Phishing only occurs via email channels, and spoofing covers all other channels including SMS and voice"], a: 0, e: "Spoofing is a technique (forging identity); phishing is an attack pattern (eliciting credentials/information). Phishing often uses spoofing, but each can occur without the other." },
    { i: "4.1.3", c: "4.1", t: "MFA factors", d: 1, q: "Multi-factor authentication adds a layer of security by requiring:", o: ["Two separate passwords, used in sequence, ideally of different lengths and character sets", "Authentication factors from at least two different categories: knowledge, possession, inherence", "Two distinct email addresses, one for the login link, the other to confirm the session is genuine", "Two different browsers, run in parallel, the second confirming the credentials entered in the first"], a: 1, e: "MFA combines factors of different kinds: something you know (password), have (token, phone), are (biometric). Two passwords are still one factor." },
    { i: "4.1.4", c: "4.1", t: "SMS 2FA weakness", d: 2, q: "Compared to SMS-based 2FA, authenticator apps and hardware keys are generally:", o: ["Less secure", "More resistant to SIM-swap and to certain phishing techniques", "Identical in security", "Only for IT staff"], a: 1, e: "SMS codes can be intercepted via SIM-swap and SS7 attacks, and are phishable. TOTP apps and especially FIDO2/WebAuthn hardware keys raise the bar substantially." },
    { i: "4.1.5", c: "4.1", t: "At rest vs in transit", d: 3, q: "Your laptop has full-disk encryption and your browser uses HTTPS. Which statement is correct?", o: ["Disk encryption protects data at rest; HTTPS protects data in transit — both layers complement each other", "HTTPS encrypts everything end-to-end, which makes the additional layer of disk encryption redundant", "Disk encryption also covers network eavesdropping because it scrambles data before it leaves the device", "Both controls describe the same encryption mechanism; only the marketing labels applied differ in practice"], a: 0, e: "Encryption at rest protects stored data if the device is lost or stolen. Encryption in transit (TLS/HTTPS) protects data crossing networks. Each addresses a different threat." },
    { i: "4.1.6", c: "4.1", t: "HTTPS limits", d: 2, q: "A website has a valid HTTPS padlock. What does this guarantee?", o: ["The site processes personal data lawfully and is fully GDPR-compliant in every EU region", "The site's owner is trustworthy and the content on the page is honest and accurate", "The connection is encrypted and the domain has been validated by a certificate authority", "Nothing meaningful — HTTPS padlocks can be issued without any verification of the site"], a: 2, e: "HTTPS encrypts the channel and authenticates the domain. It does not prove the site's owner is honest, lawful, or compliant — phishing sites routinely use HTTPS." },
    { i: "4.1.7", c: "4.1", t: "Public Wi-Fi", d: 2, q: "You must work from a café using public Wi-Fi. The most prudent baseline is to:", o: ["Disable HTTPS to save bandwidth on a constrained café network, so that pages load faster on the device", "Use the institution's VPN, keep HTTPS active throughout, and avoid logins to highly sensitive systems", "Trust the network because the password is shared with paying customers, the staff, and a few regulars", "Use Bluetooth tethering from a personal phone since Bluetooth links are private between the two devices"], a: 1, e: "VPN + HTTPS combine encryption layers; minimising sensitive logins reduces blast radius." },
    { i: "4.1.8", c: "4.1", t: "Patching", d: 1, q: "Which is the single highest-leverage hygiene control for most organisations?", o: ["Buying an expensive premium antivirus product across every endpoint in the organisation's fleet", "Promptly applying operating-system and application security updates as the vendors release them", "Refreshing the company logo and visual identity so phishing impersonators are easier to spot", "Adding more firewall layers around the network perimeter so external traffic is filtered more strictly"], a: 1, e: "Most successful breaches exploit known, unpatched vulnerabilities. Timely patching is consistently rated by ENISA, NCSC and CISA as the top-leverage control." },
    { i: "4.2.1", c: "4.2", t: "Controller vs processor", d: 3, q: "Your unit at the Commission contracts a private cloud provider to host citizen feedback survey data. Under GDPR, who must notify the supervisory authority within 72 hours of a personal-data breach on the cloud provider's systems?", o: ["The cloud provider, because the breach occurred on the systems that the provider directly operates", "Only the cloud provider's data-protection officer, who is the named contact for the supervisory authority", "Your unit as the controller, informed of the breach by the cloud provider acting as a data processor", "No-one external to the contract; internal documentation kept by the parties is sufficient under GDPR"], a: 2, e: "The Article 33 obligation is on the controller. The processor must inform the controller 'without undue delay' under Art 33(2). The 72-hour clock runs from the controller's awareness." },
    { i: "4.2.2", c: "4.2", t: "GDPR principles", d: 2, q: "Which is NOT one of the GDPR principles in Article 5?", o: ["Purpose limitation", "Data minimisation", "Mandatory cross-border transfer", "Storage limitation"], a: 2, e: "Article 5 lists: lawfulness/fairness/transparency, purpose limitation, data minimisation, accuracy, storage limitation, integrity and confidentiality, accountability." },
    { i: "4.2.3", c: "4.2", t: "Lawful bases", d: 3, q: "Which is NOT a recognised lawful basis under Article 6 GDPR for processing personal data?", o: ["Consent", "Performance of a contract with the data subject", "Best commercial interest of any competitor", "Compliance with a legal obligation"], a: 2, e: "The six bases are: consent, contract, legal obligation, vital interests, public task, legitimate interests. Generic commercial interest of a third party is not a basis." },
    { i: "4.2.4", c: "4.2", t: "Pseudonymisation", d: 3, q: "Pseudonymised data under GDPR is:", o: ["Outside the scope of the regulation because direct identifiers have been replaced with synthetic tokens", "Still personal data because re-identification remains possible with additional information held separately", "The same as anonymised data once the mapping table is held by a separate department within the controller", "Always treated as special-category data under Article 9 because tokens are reversible to identifiable persons"], a: 1, e: "Pseudonymised data remain personal data because the link can be restored. Only fully anonymised data falls outside GDPR." },
    { i: "4.2.5", c: "4.2", t: "Special-category", d: 2, q: "Which counts as 'special-category' data under Article 9 GDPR?", o: ["A person's name", "A person's professional email", "A person's health data", "A person's office number"], a: 2, e: "Article 9 lists: racial/ethnic origin, political opinions, religious beliefs, trade-union membership, genetic, biometric for identification, health, sex life, sexual orientation." },
    { i: "4.2.6", c: "4.2", t: "72-hour rule", d: 3, q: "GDPR requires notification of a personal-data breach to the supervisory authority:", o: ["Within 24 hours of becoming aware, in most cases, regardless of the level of risk the breach may pose", "Within 72 hours of becoming aware, in most cases, except where the breach is unlikely to pose a risk", "Within 30 calendar days, with a preliminary notification submitted as soon as is practicable", "Within 7 days, but only when more than 1000 data subjects are affected by the breach in question"], a: 1, e: "Article 33: notify the supervisory authority within 72 hours where feasible, with reasoned justification if delayed, unless the breach is unlikely to result in a risk to rights and freedoms." },
    { i: "4.2.7", c: "4.2", t: "Erasure not absolute", d: 2, q: "Which is NOT a data subject right under GDPR?", o: ["Right of access", "Right to rectification", "Right to demand deletion of any data without exception", "Right to data portability"], a: 2, e: "The right to erasure (Art 17) has explicit grounds and exceptions (e.g. freedom of expression, legal obligation, public interest). It is not unconditional." },
    { i: "4.2.8", c: "4.2", t: "Cookie consent", d: 2, q: "Under EU rules (ePrivacy + GDPR), valid cookie consent for non-essential cookies must be:", o: ["Pre-ticked checkboxes shown by default, for user convenience, ease of use, and quick banner completion", "Freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous through a clear affirmative action by the user", "Implied by the user's continued browsing of the site after the cookie banner has been displayed", "Documented in the privacy policy alone, with cookies dropped on first page load before any prompt"], a: 1, e: "The CJEU's Planet49 ruling and EDPB guidance confirm that pre-ticked boxes and continued browsing are not valid consent. A clear opt-in action is required." },
    { i: "4.3.1", c: "4.3", t: "Right to disconnect", d: 2, q: "The 'right to disconnect' refers to:", o: ["A right to switch off antivirus software temporarily so it does not interrupt focused work sessions", "A worker's right not to engage in work-related electronic communication outside working hours", "A right to use a single device for both personal and professional digital activities and communication", "A right to free public Wi-Fi access in workplaces and public buildings funded by the local authority"], a: 1, e: "The right to disconnect is recognised in EU labour-policy debate and in DigComp 2.2's RW examples. Several Member States have legislated it explicitly." },
    { i: "4.3.2", c: "4.3", t: "Dark patterns", d: 3, q: "A subscription page makes it easy to subscribe but hides the cancellation flow behind multiple confusing screens. This is an example of:", o: ["Good UX — the design correctly prioritises the most common user task on the page", "A 'dark pattern' — deceptive design regulated under the EU Digital Services Act", "A privacy-by-design feature that limits how often users disclose personal data", "An accessibility improvement reducing cognitive load for users with disabilities"], a: 1, e: "Asymmetric friction between sign-up and cancellation is a textbook dark pattern. The DSA explicitly prohibits dark patterns on online platforms." },
    { i: "4.3.3", c: "4.3", t: "Bystander cyberbullying", d: 1, q: "A colleague shows you sustained, repeated, hostile messages they are receiving on a public team channel. The most appropriate professional response is to:", o: ["Tell them to ignore it — engaging only encourages the sender and prolongs the situation", "Acknowledge the harm, help preserve evidence, and support them in reporting formally", "Reply in the channel with sharp counter-messages so the harasser feels the pushback too", "Delete the offending messages on their behalf so the channel returns to a calm state"], a: 1, e: "Acknowledgement, evidence preservation, and formal reporting are the recognised support pattern. Counter-attacks escalate; deletion may destroy evidence." },
    { i: "4.3.4", c: "4.3", t: "Ergonomics", d: 1, q: "Which practice best supports physical well-being during long computer-based work?", o: ["Working in dim ambient light, dimming the screen, and reducing contrast so the eyes rest over the day", "Following a routine of breaks at 20-minute intervals, with correct chair and screen height, and varied posture", "Disabling notifications, blocking calendar alerts, and silencing the device for multi-hour focus blocks", "Closing the curtains throughout the day, switching off overhead lights, and lowering the laptop brightness"], a: 1, e: "Regular breaks, ergonomic setup, and varied posture are well-evidenced. Dim light actually increases eye strain by widening the contrast with a bright screen." },
    { i: "4.3.5", c: "4.3", t: "Loot boxes", d: 2, q: "A 'free' mobile game uses 'loot boxes' that deliver random rewards in exchange for in-app currency. The principal well-being concern is:", o: ["Bright animations and sound effects can be over-stimulating, posing a sensory risk for children playing", "The mechanic uses variable-ratio reinforcement similar to gambling, with risks for younger users", "Most loot-box games have too few levels, so players exhaust the content within a few sessions", "Continuous in-game animations drain battery quickly and shorten the device's daily usable time"], a: 1, e: "Loot boxes share psychological mechanics with gambling and are regulated as gambling in some Member States." },
    { i: "4.3.6", c: "4.3", t: "Notification hygiene", d: 1, q: "A common evidence-based recommendation for digital well-being and focus is to:", o: ["Leave all notifications enabled so important messages are seen as soon as they arrive on the device", "Disable non-essential notifications and check messages in batches at predictable intervals during the day", "Keep the phone within reach throughout the working day so that no incoming message is ever missed", "Restrict working hours to a single core app so notifications outside that app can be ignored entirely"], a: 1, e: "Constant interruptions degrade attention and increase stress. Selective notifications and batched checking are widely recommended in workplace digital-wellbeing guidance." },
    { i: "4.3.7", c: "4.3", t: "Harassment pattern", d: 2, q: "What pattern most reliably distinguishes online harassment from a single offensive comment?", o: ["The use of capital letters, aggressive punctuation, and pointed emphasis spread across the message body", "Repetition, persistence, and a power imbalance directed at the same target across an extended period", "The presence of emoji, reaction icons, and short replies that signal mocking rather than friendly intent", "A long message with multiple paragraphs, dense quoting, and overwhelming length for the target to reply"], a: 1, e: "Harassment frameworks (e.g. EU-OSHA, ILO) emphasise repetition and unwanted, hostile pattern, often with power imbalance — distinct from one-off rudeness." },
    { i: "4.3.8", c: "4.3", t: "Persuasive design", d: 3, q: "Infinite-scroll feeds, pull-to-refresh, and streak counters are examples of:", o: ["Accessibility features designed to reduce cognitive load for users with disabilities", "Persuasive-design patterns engineered to maximise time-on-app and engagement", "Encryption protocols that secure session data exchanged between client and server", "Privacy-by-design tools that minimise the personal data collected during a session"], a: 1, e: "Persuasive design borrows from behavioural psychology to drive engagement. DigComp 2.2 explicitly raises awareness of these patterns and their well-being effects." },
    { i: "4.4.1", c: "4.4", t: "WEEE", d: 1, q: "What is the recommended end-of-life route for an old laptop with personal data on it?", o: ["Throw it in the household residual-waste bin so the disposal chain handles it like any other rubbish", "Securely wipe or destroy the storage, then recycle through a certified WEEE or e-waste channel", "Leave it on the street so a passer-by who can still use the device collects it before collection day", "Bury it in the garden so the metal casing can degrade slowly without producing immediate landfill"], a: 1, e: "WEEE channels recover materials and prevent toxic releases. Secure data deletion or physical destruction protects personal data first." },
    { i: "4.4.2", c: "4.4", t: "Video footprint", d: 2, q: "Which choice typically reduces the energy footprint of a video conference?", o: ["Always running at the highest resolution available, since modern codecs offset the cost", "Turning video off when not needed for interaction and preferring audio-only where sufficient", "Adding more participants so each receives a smaller share of the encoded bandwidth", "Recording every call locally so it can be replayed later instead of running live again"], a: 1, e: "Video streams dominate bandwidth and indirectly energy consumption. Voice-only and lower-resolution options are simple, well-recognised reductions." },
    { i: "4.4.3", c: "4.4", t: "AI energy", d: 2, q: "Training large AI models is energy-intensive. A reasonable consumer-level practice that supports environmental sustainability is to:", o: ["Run the largest available model on each query so the answer benefits from the most capable tool", "Match the model size to the task and use smaller or deterministic tools when they are sufficient", "Run several models in parallel for each query and keep whichever output looks best to the reader", "Train a private model for each question so the model is fully tailored to the user's task at hand"], a: 1, e: "Right-sizing the tool to the task (smaller LLMs, deterministic tools where applicable) reduces compute and energy use without sacrificing utility." },
    { i: "4.4.4", c: "4.4", t: "Right to repair", d: 2, q: "The EU's 'right to repair' policy aims primarily to:", o: ["Oblige manufacturers to repair all consumer goods, free of charge, for the original purchaser of the product", "Extend product lifetimes through better access to spare parts, information, and reasonable repair conditions", "Restrict repair work to certified technicians, raise the bar for quality, and ban repairs by amateurs", "Replace recycling rules, exempt repairable products from waste regulations, and shift collection to retailers"], a: 1, e: "Right to repair (Directive 2024/1799) facilitates repair of consumer goods, supporting circular-economy goals." },
    { i: "4.4.5", c: "4.4", t: "Cloud carbon", d: 2, q: "Choosing a cloud provider whose data centre runs primarily on renewable energy is one way to:", o: ["Avoid GDPR", "Reduce the carbon footprint of digital services", "Increase storage by 10x", "Disable encryption"], a: 1, e: "Energy mix of underlying data centres is a recognised lever in green-IT procurement." },
    { i: "4.4.6", c: "4.4", t: "Ecodesign", d: 2, q: "The EU Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation (ESPR, 2024) for digital products encourages:", o: ["Single-use product design, where each generation is built, sold, and used for the workload it shipped with", "Durability, reparability, recyclability, and continued access to firmware updates after sale", "Mandatory annual product replacement so devices keep pace with software-security expectations", "Closed proprietary chargers so each manufacturer can certify the safety of its own power chain"], a: 1, e: "ESPR aims at extending product lifetimes and reducing material waste, including for electronics." },
    { i: "4.4.7", c: "4.4", t: "Print vs digital", d: 1, q: "For a one-page leaflet read once and discarded, the lowest-impact distribution is typically:", o: ["Glossy full-colour mass mail to most households so the message usually reaches the largest possible audience", "A digital version delivered to those who want it, with print on demand for those who prefer paper", "Printing one copy per resident regardless of opt-in so coverage is guaranteed across the territory", "No distribution at all, since any leaflet duplicates information that is already available on the website"], a: 1, e: "Targeted digital distribution avoids material waste; print-on-demand respects accessibility preferences." },
    { i: "4.4.8", c: "4.4", t: "Lifecycle impact", d: 2, q: "From a sustainability perspective, the highest-impact decision over a laptop's lifecycle is usually:", o: ["The brand's logo colour", "Whether it is replaced every two years vs every five years", "The keyboard layout", "The screen brightness setting"], a: 1, e: "Manufacturing dominates lifecycle impact for most consumer electronics. Extending replacement cycles delivers a larger reduction than most operational tweaks." },
    { i: "5.1.1", c: "5.1", t: "First-line", d: 1, q: "A colleague's laptop will not connect to Wi-Fi. The most efficient first-line steps are:", o: ["Reformat the disk, reinstall the system, and remove any corrupted network configuration before retrying", "Check airplane mode and the Wi-Fi switch, restart the adapter, and confirm the network is up for others", "Replace the laptop right away, ship the failed unit back, and reissue a fresh device to the colleague", "Reinstall the operating system, rebuild the network stack, and reapply the default profile from scratch"], a: 1, e: "The fastest fixes address the most common causes (mode switches, transient adapter state, network outages)." },
    { i: "5.1.2", c: "5.1", t: "Error codes", d: 2, q: "An application shows a cryptic error code. The most productive next step is:", o: ["Ignore it and continue working — most cryptic codes resolve themselves on the next session", "Note the exact wording and code, then search the vendor's documentation or knowledge base", "Click through the dialogue repeatedly until the application clears the message and continues", "Restart the device five times in a row to force the error state out of cached system memory"], a: 1, e: "Error codes are searchable identifiers. Capturing the exact wording lets you find vendor documentation or known-issue threads efficiently." },
    { i: "5.1.3", c: "5.1", t: "Browser-side state", d: 2, q: "A web app works for colleagues but not for you. As a quick test, you should try:", o: ["Reinstalling the operating system to clear any corrupt drivers that may be interfering with the app", "Clearing browser cache and cookies for the site, or trying a private window or a different browser", "Replacing the keyboard so input issues that may be confusing the app's form handlers are ruled out", "Disabling the antivirus and the firewall completely so no security software interferes with the request"], a: 1, e: "Stale cache, expired cookies, and corrupted local state are common causes of 'works for them, not for me'. A private window isolates the variable cleanly." },
    { i: "5.1.4", c: "5.1", t: "DNS isolation", d: 3, q: "You can ping google.com but cannot reach the website in your browser. The most likely culprit is:", o: ["A browser-layer or proxy issue (since name resolution itself succeeded)", "A faulty graphics card", "No-one else uses the internet", "Your printer driver"], a: 0, e: "If ping resolves the name and reaches the host, name resolution is fine but a browser-layer or proxy issue is likely. The point is to isolate layers." },
    { i: "5.1.5", c: "5.1", t: "Hardware vs software", d: 2, q: "Your screen flickers in every application. Which test best distinguishes hardware from software causes?", o: ["Boot from a different OS / live USB and observe the same monitor", "Try a different keyboard", "Reinstall one application", "Close the laptop lid"], a: 0, e: "Booting an alternative OS isolates whether the symptom follows the hardware or the OS install. If flicker persists, hardware is implicated." },
    { i: "5.1.6", c: "5.1", t: "Ransomware response", d: 1, q: "A laptop displays a serious-looking warning that it has been encrypted by ransomware demanding payment. You should:", o: ["Pay the ransom through the listed channel, follow the instructions, and recover the files as fast as possible", "Disconnect the device from the network, escalate to IT or security right away, and avoid paying any ransom", "Reformat the disk, wipe the malware, and restore the latest backup once the operating system is clean", "Forward the warning to colleagues, share the screenshot in team chat, and warn them about the attack pattern"], a: 1, e: "Containment first (network isolation), then expert response. Paying funds criminal operations, gives no guarantee, and may trigger legal/sanctions issues." },
    { i: "5.1.7", c: "5.1", t: "Cross-browser", d: 2, q: "A web app behaves wrongly in one browser but works in another. The most likely cause is:", o: ["Defective hardware in the device, a failing component, or a damaged peripheral altering input", "A browser-specific compatibility issue, an interfering extension, or a stale cache in that browser", "A virus on the device, malware filtering some traffic, or hijacked network resolution rules", "A faulty router, intermittent loss of upstream connectivity, or congestion on the local network"], a: 1, e: "Cross-browser differences narrow the issue to browser-side state or compatibility." },
    { i: "5.1.8", c: "5.1", t: "Documentation", d: 2, q: "You solve a tricky issue after a long search. The professional next step is to:", o: ["Forget about it", "Document the symptom, root cause and fix in a place your team can find later", "Email the manufacturer", "Hide the documentation"], a: 1, e: "Documenting solved issues builds organisational memory and saves future hours. DigComp 5.4 also frames this as supporting others." },
    { i: "5.2.1", c: "5.2", t: "IaaS/PaaS/SaaS", d: 3, q: "Which best matches the cloud service models?", o: ["IaaS = applications, PaaS = managed storage, SaaS = the underlying network layer", "IaaS = raw infrastructure (VMs, storage), PaaS = managed platform, SaaS = ready-to-use apps", "IaaS, PaaS and SaaS describe the same model under different vendors' marketing names", "IaaS targets individual users; PaaS targets SMEs; SaaS is reserved for large enterprises"], a: 1, e: "IaaS rents infrastructure. PaaS provides a managed platform. SaaS delivers complete applications. Each shifts more responsibility to the provider." },
    { i: "5.2.2", c: "5.2", t: "Cloud vs edge", d: 3, q: "Edge computing differs from cloud computing principally because it:", o: ["Is consistently more expensive than centralised cloud because each edge node is provisioned separately", "Processes data near where it is produced to reduce latency and the bandwidth carried upstream", "Cannot use encryption because the limited compute on edge devices does not support modern ciphers", "Requires no electricity since edge devices typically harvest power from ambient signals or motion"], a: 1, e: "Edge computing brings computation closer to the data source. Latency-sensitive (industrial, medical, automotive) and bandwidth-constrained scenarios benefit." },
    { i: "5.2.3", c: "5.2", t: "RPA fit", d: 2, q: "Your unit processes hundreds of identical form responses each week. The best fit is generally:", o: ["Hire additional permanent staff so that throughput scales linearly with the volume of incoming forms", "Automate via workflow / RPA / scripting and keep a human review step for the edge cases that arise", "Procure a new high-speed printer so paper handling is no longer the bottleneck during peak periods", "Apply manual triple-checking so each form passes through three reviewers before any data are recorded"], a: 1, e: "Repetitive, rule-based work is a textbook automation target. Keeping humans in the loop for exceptions preserves judgement where it adds value." },
    { i: "5.2.4", c: "5.2", t: "Tool to task", d: 1, q: "Which is the most appropriate tool for occasional collaborative editing of a short text?", o: ["A relational database", "A shared cloud document with track changes", "A 3D modelling program", "A spreadsheet macro"], a: 1, e: "Match tool to task: a shared text document is the right fit. Databases, modelling tools and macros are over-engineered for short collaborative text." },
    { i: "5.2.5", c: "5.2", t: "Accessible content", d: 2, q: "You need to share information with a user who relies on a screen reader. The best presentation is:", o: ["A scanned-image PDF of a printed poster, with the page photographed and captured at a high resolution", "A properly tagged document or web page with semantic structure, headings, and alt-text on every figure", "A handwritten note (such as a memo) that has been photographed and shared as a high-resolution image", "An audio file of the message, sent without a transcript, since the user is comfortable with audio playback"], a: 1, e: "Tagged, semantic content is fully perceivable to assistive technology. Image-only PDFs and untranscribed audio are inaccessible by default." },
    { i: "5.2.6", c: "5.2", t: "AI vs deterministic", d: 3, q: "You need to extract a known fixed pattern (e.g. all dates in DD/MM/YYYY format) from a large file. The most appropriate tool is generally:", o: ["A generative-AI chatbot, prompted with the file content, asked to list every date it sees in order", "A deterministic tool, such as a regular expression or parser — exact, fast, and reproducible", "A handwritten lookup pass (such as eye-balling the file end-to-end), recording each date in a list", "A new database, indexed on the file content, queried for the date pattern with structured search"], a: 1, e: "Where the rule is exact and stable, deterministic methods beat probabilistic ones on accuracy, speed, cost, and reproducibility. AI is best where rules are fuzzy." },
    { i: "5.2.7", c: "5.2", t: "Storage choice", d: 1, q: "Which is the most suitable storage choice for a 5 GB working dataset shared by a small team that edits it daily?", o: ["Email attachments", "A shared cloud folder or team drive with versioning and access control", "Personal USB sticks", "Print-outs in a binder"], a: 1, e: "Daily collaborative editing needs a single source of truth, version history, and controlled access — the value proposition of a team drive." },
    { i: "5.2.8", c: "5.2", t: "Audit logs", d: 2, q: "Your manager requests a chronological view of who did what on a long project. The best response is to:", o: ["Ask everyone on the team to recall their main contributions and assemble a written summary together", "Provide an export from the project tool's audit or activity log, filtered for the relevant date range", "Recreate the timeline manually from email threads and chat history that the team has kept on the project", "Take a photo of the team's wall planner and use that as a record of who worked on which tasks"], a: 1, e: "Modern collaboration tools maintain audit / activity logs precisely for accountability." },
    { i: "5.3.1", c: "5.3", t: "AI for ideation", d: 2, q: "Used responsibly, a generative-AI tool is most useful in early creative work as:", o: ["A definitive expert whose judgement settles disagreements between contributors on the team", "A divergent ideation partner that broadens the option space for the team to evaluate critically", "A replacement for the human expertise that the team would normally bring to the early-stage work", "A neutral source of factual statements that the team can drop into the brief without further review"], a: 1, e: "Generative AI is best treated as a divergent thinking aid: produce many options, then apply human judgement, expertise, and verification." },
    { i: "5.3.2", c: "5.3", t: "IoT example", d: 2, q: "A municipality deploys soil-moisture sensors in parks to optimise irrigation. This is an example of:", o: ["A generative-AI deployment in which a model produces irrigation schedules from training data", "An Internet-of-Things deployment with networked sensors feeding a control system in real time", "A blockchain deployment that uses distributed ledgers to record sensor readings tamper-evidently", "A quantum-computing deployment in which sensor data feeds a quantum optimisation algorithm"], a: 1, e: "IoT = networked physical sensors/actuators producing data for analysis or control. This is a textbook smart-city example." },
    { i: "5.3.3", c: "5.3", t: "Prototyping", d: 1, q: "In design thinking, the purpose of a prototype is principally to:", o: ["Be the final delivered product, with later iterations only adding polish on top of the same artefact", "Make ideas tangible cheaply enough to test assumptions and learn before fully committing to a build", "Replace user research entirely because the prototype itself answers the questions research would ask", "Save engineering time later by locking in the implementation choices that the build phase will follow"], a: 1, e: "Prototypes exist to be tested and discarded if needed. Their value is the speed of learning, not the polish of the artefact." },
    { i: "5.3.4", c: "5.3", t: "Citizen science", d: 2, q: "Citizen-science platforms (e.g. for biodiversity monitoring) rely on members of the public contributing observations. Their main value is:", o: ["Replacing professional scientists with volunteers, removing the need for trained researchers", "Scaling data collection across places and times beyond what professionals alone can cover", "Providing free promotion for the funding institution running the platform online", "Substituting for the formal public consultations required by EU environmental directives"], a: 1, e: "Citizen science complements professional science by extending coverage. Quality control (training, validation, redundancy) is essential." },
    { i: "5.3.5", c: "5.3", t: "AR vs VR", d: 2, q: "Augmented reality differs from virtual reality because:", o: ["AR renders content only in 2D, while VR is rendered as a fully three-dimensional immersive medium", "AR overlays digital content on the real-world view, while VR replaces the view with a synthetic environment", "AR works without any sensors, since the camera feed alone is enough to anchor virtual objects in the scene", "VR is the older of the two technologies, and AR has emerged more recently in mainstream consumer headsets"], a: 1, e: "AR augments reality with overlays. VR replaces the user's visual environment entirely. Mixed reality (MR) blends the two." },
    { i: "5.3.6", c: "5.3", t: "Hackathon", d: 1, q: "A hackathon is best understood as:", o: ["An authorised cyber-attack exercise that probes production systems for unpatched vulnerabilities", "A time-bounded event where teams rapidly prototype solutions to a problem for learning or innovation", "A long-term external consulting engagement that delivers a roadmap and detailed staffing plan", "A regulatory audit conducted by a supervisory authority on an organisation's digital systems"], a: 1, e: "'Hack' here means rapid creation, not intrusion. Hackathons emphasise speed, collaboration, and exploratory prototyping." },
    { i: "5.3.7", c: "5.3", t: "Responsible AI deployment", d: 3, q: "Your team wants to deploy an AI tool to triage citizen complaints automatically. The most responsible approach is to:", o: ["Deploy across the full caseload first, monitor compliance in production, and inform citizens after launch", "Pilot with human oversight, evaluate on representative data, document the system, and ensure recourse", "Test on synthetic complaints, deploy after sign-off, and rely on the synthetic test to confirm fairness", "Deploy without formal evaluation, monitor user feedback during operation, and fix issues as reported"], a: 1, e: "Pilot, evaluate on representative data, document, and provide recourse — aligned with both DigComp 2.2 AI annex and the EU AI Act high-risk system obligations." },
    { i: "5.3.8", c: "5.3", t: "Simulation", d: 2, q: "A simulation is most useful when:", o: ["The idea can be tested cheaply in the real world, the field results come back quickly, and the cost is low", "Real-world testing would be too costly, slow, or risky, and a model captures the relevant dynamics", "The team wants to avoid producing detailed documentation, design notes, or specifications for the system", "The deliverable is a static report, the audience is internal, and no interactive exploration is required"], a: 1, e: "Simulations shine where reality is too costly or risky to probe directly (epidemics, evacuations, crash testing, climate)." },
    { i: "5.4.1", c: "5.4", t: "Self-assessment tools", d: 1, q: "Tools like DigCompSAT and MyDigiSkills are intended to:", o: ["Replace formal national qualifications so users skip accredited training when seeking digital roles", "Help citizens self-assess digital competence against DigComp and identify their own learning needs", "Test employers' hiring practices and benchmark them against the DigComp competence framework", "Issue legally binding certificates that satisfy regulated professions' continuing-education rules"], a: 1, e: "They are self-assessment instruments aligned with DigComp. They support reflection and learning planning rather than formal certification." },
    { i: "5.4.2", c: "5.4", t: "Lifelong learning", d: 1, q: "Which mindset best supports keeping digital competence current?", o: ["Learn the basics once during initial training and rely on those for the rest of one's career", "Treat digital competence as a continuous process of small updates, self-review and exposure", "Avoid adopting new tools so that hard-won proficiency in current tools is not undermined", "Wait for the employer to mandate retraining and only invest time when explicitly required to"], a: 1, e: "Continuous, low-friction learning is more sustainable than rare crash courses. DigComp 5.4 frames competence as a moving target tied to lifelong learning." },
    { i: "5.4.3", c: "5.4", t: "Micro-credentials", d: 2, q: "A 'micro-credential' is best described as:", o: ["A non-accredited diploma usually issued by a private provider outside the formal national education system", "A small verifiable certification of a specific skill, typically issued digitally and stackable to others", "A small EU grant supporting short professional-development courses for civil servants in EU institutions", "A short numeric token used as a password substitute when authenticating on small-screen mobile devices"], a: 1, e: "Micro-credentials (Council Recommendation 2022/C 243/02) are short, verifiable certifications stackable into broader qualifications." },
    { i: "5.4.4", c: "5.4", t: "Targeted learning", d: 1, q: "You realise you struggle with cybersecurity concepts. The most productive response is to:", o: ["Ignore the gap and rely on the IT team to handle anything cybersecurity-related on your behalf", "Take a structured course or self-paced resource targeting that area and practise the concepts", "Avoid the digital tasks where the gap shows up and rotate them to colleagues with more experience", "Hire a permanent assistant who can sit alongside you and handle cybersecurity decisions for you"], a: 1, e: "Targeted, structured learning closes specific gaps. Avoidance compounds the problem and is professionally limiting." },
    { i: "5.4.5", c: "5.4", t: "Supporting others", d: 2, q: "DigComp 5.4 also includes 'supporting others'. A practical application is to:", o: ["Take over digital tasks from less-experienced colleagues so they can focus on their primary work", "Mentor a less-experienced colleague or document a process so others can use it independently", "Keep specialised knowledge private to remain the team's go-to expert and protect role security", "Avoid teaching colleagues so they remain free to learn at their own pace without external pressure"], a: 1, e: "Mentoring and documentation are cited as part of the competence. They scale the team's capability and reinforce one's own understanding." },
    { i: "5.4.6", c: "5.4", t: "AI/data trends", d: 2, q: "Why is staying current with AI and data trends specifically called out in DigComp 2.2?", o: ["Because trends rarely affect public-administration work and are unimportant for civil servants", "Because AI and data practices evolve rapidly and directly affect citizens' rights and work", "Because following the latest tools is a fashionable signal of digital fluency among staff", "Because DigComp will soon be replaced and staff need to anticipate the next framework"], a: 1, e: "DigComp 2.2's emphasis on AI literacy reflects the speed of change and the consequential effects on individuals." },
    { i: "5.4.7", c: "5.4", t: "MOOCs", d: 1, q: "A MOOC (Massive Open Online Course) is best characterised as:", o: ["A face-to-face seminar series streamed online for participants who typically cannot attend the host venue", "An online course open to many learners at low or no cost, often with paid certification as an option", "A private one-to-one tutoring service delivered remotely by a paid subject-matter expert tutor", "A new programming language designed to build large-scale interactive learning platforms online"], a: 1, e: "MOOCs are scalable open online courses, often hosted on platforms like Coursera, edX, FutureLearn, or the EU's own initiatives." },
    { i: "5.4.8", c: "5.4", t: "Blind spots", d: 2, q: "Which approach is most likely to reveal blind spots in your digital competence?", o: ["Sticking to the tasks you already know well, refining only the methods you already use, over time", "Periodically tackling unfamiliar tools, seeking peer feedback, and using structured self-assessment", "Avoiding feedback from peers and managers, since unsolicited input typically disrupts focused work", "Working alone on personal practice tasks, well away from team noise and any regular work environment"], a: 1, e: "Stretch tasks, feedback, and assessments expose unknown unknowns. Routine alone tends to reinforce existing patterns and hides gaps." }
];

